OSI Model

The OSI Model is a conceptual framework that explains how communication happens between two systems over a network.
It has 7 layers, and each layer has a specific role.

---

OSI Layers

1. Application Layer

This is the layer where users interact with the network.
It provides network services to applications.

Examples:
HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, DNS, SMTP, POP3, IMAP, Telnet, SSH

---

2. Presentation Layer

This layer is responsible for data formatting, encryption, and compression.
It converts data into a readable format and also decrypts and decompresses data when received.

---

3. Session Layer

This layer manages and maintains sessions (connections) between systems.
It is responsible for establishing, maintaining, and terminating connections.

---

4. Transport Layer

This layer is responsible for end-to-end data delivery.
It ensures data is delivered correctly and in order.

Protocols:

- TCP (reliable, connection-oriented)
- UDP (fast, connectionless, less reliable)

---

5. Network Layer

This layer handles IP addressing and routing.
It ensures data is sent from source to destination across networks.

---

6. Data Link Layer

This layer works with MAC addresses and handles communication within the same network.
It is responsible for error detection and frame transmission.

---

7. Physical Layer

This layer deals with physical components like cables, signals, and hardware.
It is responsible for transmitting raw bits over the network.